---
import BrowserSupport from "../components/BrowserSupport.astro";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>Native CSS nesting</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the most obvious Sass feature that is now native — everyone in the
      room has written &:hover or &__modifier.
    </p>
    <p>The sell is simple: same syntax, no compiler, no build step.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">Sass syntax, without the Sass</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      🪆 <span>Collocate rules </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >with their context</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      ✂️ <span>No more </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >selector repetition</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🚫 <span>No build step, </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >no preprocessor</span
      ><span> dependency</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Ask the room: who uses nesting as the main reason they still reach for
      Sass? Almost everyone will raise a hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      The point: not only can you remove the preprocessor, you keep the same
      authoring experience.
    </p>
    <p>
      Bonus worth mentioning: you can also nest @media and @container inside a
      rule — co-location of responsive rules was one of the hardest things to
      give up when writing plain CSS.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Nesting</span> — Sass feature, compiler required 🪆
  </h5>
  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="center">
        <span class="tag"
          >Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">build-time only</span></span
        >
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="nav.scss">
        <code style="font-size: 0.7em" is:raw class="language-scss">
    nav {
        display: flex;
        gap: 1rem;

        a {
            color: $brand;

            &:hover { color: darken($brand, 15%); }
            &[aria-current="page"] { font-weight: 700; }  
        }
    }</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Everyone recognises this. It's the Sass every design system is built on.
    </p>
    <p>
      The problem is invisible: the browser never sees this file. It sees a
      flat, compiled output — nesting gone, variables resolved.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Nesting — native, zero build</span> 🌐
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="nav.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em" is:raw class="language-css">
    nav {
        display: flex;
        gap: 1rem;

        a {
            color: var(--brand);

            &:hover { color: color-mix(in oklch, var(--brand), black 15%); }
            &[aria-current="page"] { font-weight: 700; }
        }
    }</code></pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Same structure as the Sass version — the browser parses it directly.</p>
    <p>
      No repeated selector, no lifting out: the co-location benefit that was
      Sass-only until recently. @media and @container nest the same way.
    </p>
    <p>
      color-mix replaces darken() — we'll dig into it in the colors section,
      coming next. One less reason to reach for a preprocessor.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="CSS nesting"
  chrome="120"
  firefox="117"
  safari="17.2"
  status="All evergreen browsers"
/>
